[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 14.6: Patient Flow and Bed Assignment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Medium-Complex · **Phase:** Production · **Estimated Cost:** ~$500-1,500/month (solver compute + real-time infrastructure)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It's 2 PM on a Tuesday and the emergency department has 14 patients waiting for inpatient beds. The charge nurse on 4-West has two discharges "pending" (the doctors signed the orders an hour ago, but transport hasn't moved the patients yet). The telemetry unit is full, but three of those patients could step down to med-surg if anyone had time to reassess them. A patient in the ICU is ready to transfer out, but the only open step-down bed is on a unit that doesn't have the right nursing skill mix for their drip. Meanwhile, a direct admission from a clinic is arriving in 45 minutes and nobody has figured out where to put them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is patient flow. And in most hospitals, it's managed by a combination of phone calls, whiteboards, gut instinct, and a bed management coordinator who somehow keeps the whole thing in their head.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The cost of getting this wrong is enormous. ED boarding (patients waiting in the ED for inpatient beds) is one of the most studied problems in hospital operations. Boarded patients experience longer total lengths of stay, higher complication rates, and worse outcomes. The ED itself becomes gridlocked: when beds are full of boarders, new patients can't be seen, ambulances get diverted, and the whole system degrades. Studies have consistently shown that ED boarding correlates with increased mortality for both the boarding patients and the new arrivals who can't get timely care.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The financial impact is equally brutal. Every hour a patient boards in the ED costs the hospital revenue (they're occupying an ED bed but generating inpatient-level charges that often aren't fully reimbursed at ED rates). Delayed discharges mean beds aren't turning over, which means elective surgical cases get cancelled (there's your OR utilization problem from Recipe 14.5, cascading downstream). A 400-bed hospital losing even 30 minutes of unnecessary boarding per patient per day is leaving millions on the table annually.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m And here's the thing that makes this problem genuinely hard: it's not a static assignment problem. It's dynamic. The state changes constantly. Patients arrive unpredictably. Discharges happen (or don't happen) on their own timeline. Acuity levels shift. Isolation requirements appear when a lab result comes back positive. A nurse calls in sick and suddenly a unit's capacity drops. You can't solve this once and walk away. You need to re-solve it continuously.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is where optimization gets interesting. Not the quarterly batch optimization of OR blocks (Recipe 14.5), but something closer to real-time: a system that continuously evaluates the current state of the hospital and recommends the best patient-to-bed assignments given everything it knows right now.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Real-Time Assignment Optimization
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Assignment Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m At its mathematical core, bed assignment is a variant of the classic assignment problem: you have N patients who need beds and M available beds, and you want to find the best matching. In the simplest version (the "linear assignment problem"), you have a cost matrix where entry (i, j) represents the cost (or negative benefit) of assigning patient i to bed j, and you want to minimize total cost.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The Hungarian algorithm solves the basic linear assignment problem in polynomial time. It's elegant, fast, and completely insufficient for real hospital bed assignment. Why? Because the real problem has constraints that the basic formulation can't express, multiple objectives that conflict, and a dynamic element that means the "optimal" solution changes every few minutes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Constraint Formulation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The constraints in bed assignment fall into categories that range from absolute (violating them is unsafe) to preferential (violating them is suboptimal but acceptable):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hard constraints (patient safety):**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Isolation requirements: patients with airborne infections (TB, COVID, measles) must go to negative-pressure rooms. Contact isolation patients need private rooms or cohorting with same-organism patients only.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Gender separation: in semi-private rooms, patients must be same gender (with exceptions for pediatrics and some cultural contexts).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Acuity-to-unit matching: an ICU-level patient cannot go to a med-surg floor. A telemetry patient needs a monitored bed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Age-appropriate placement: pediatric patients go to pediatric units. Behavioral health patients go to secured units.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Equipment requirements: patients on certain drips, ventilators, or monitoring need beds with the right infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Operational constraints:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Unit staffing: a unit might have physical beds available but not enough nurses to safely staff them. The nurse-to-patient ratio is a real capacity limit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Skill mix: a patient on a complex cardiac drip needs a nurse certified to manage it. Not every nurse on every unit has every certification.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Anticipated discharges: a bed that's "available in 2 hours" is different from one that's available now. Do you hold it or assign someone else?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Cleaning turnaround: after discharge, a bed needs terminal cleaning (30-60 minutes typically). It's not instantly available.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Preference constraints (soft):**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Continuity of care: if a patient was on 4-West last admission, there's value in placing them there again (familiar staff, existing relationships).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Geographic clustering: patients of the same attending physician ideally land on the same unit for rounding efficiency.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Noise and environment: post-surgical patients benefit from quieter rooms. Patients with delirium risk should be near the nursing station.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Anticipated length of stay: putting a patient expected to stay 1 day in a bed that a 7-day patient will need tomorrow is suboptimal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Discharge timing: placing patients in beds that facilitate morning discharge flow (near elevators, near discharge lounges) can improve throughput.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Multi-Objective Optimization
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The real challenge isn't any single constraint. It's that you're optimizing multiple objectives simultaneously, and they conflict:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 1. **Minimize ED boarding time.** Get patients out of the ED and into beds as fast as possible.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 2. **Maximize clinical appropriateness.** Put patients in the right unit with the right level of care.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 3. **Balance unit workload.** Don't overload one unit while another sits half-empty.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 4. **Minimize transfers.** Every intra-hospital transfer is a safety risk (medication errors, communication failures, patient falls during transport).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 5. **Maximize throughput.** Optimize for the flow of patients through the system, not just the current snapshot.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m You can't maximize all of these simultaneously. Minimizing ED boarding time might mean putting a patient on a less-than-ideal unit. Balancing workload might mean sending a patient to a unit farther from their physician. The optimization needs to encode these tradeoffs explicitly through objective weights or constraint hierarchies.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A common approach is **lexicographic optimization**: satisfy the most important objective first (safety constraints), then optimize the second objective (ED boarding) subject to the first being satisfied, then the third, and so on. Alternatively, you can use a **weighted sum** approach where each objective gets a numerical weight reflecting its relative importance. The weights are policy decisions that hospital leadership must make explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Solver Selection for Real-Time Problems
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The solver choice for bed assignment is different from batch scheduling (Recipe 14.5) because of the time constraint. You need solutions in seconds, not minutes or hours.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Mixed-Integer Programming (MIP):** Still works for bed assignment, but you need to be careful about problem size. A 400-bed hospital with 30 pending assignments is a manageable MIP (hundreds of binary variables, not thousands). Modern solvers (Gurobi, OR-Tools) can solve this in under a second. But if you're re-solving every 5 minutes with a warm start, you want the solver to be fast and deterministic.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Constraint Programming (CP):** Particularly well-suited for bed assignment because the constraint structure is complex and heterogeneous. CP solvers (Google OR-Tools CP-SAT, IBM CP Optimizer) handle "if-then" constraints naturally. "If patient has airborne isolation, then room must have negative pressure" is awkward in MIP (requires big-M formulations) but natural in CP.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Greedy heuristics with local search:** For the real-time component, sometimes a fast heuristic that produces a "good enough" solution in milliseconds is better than an optimal solution that takes 30 seconds. A priority-queue approach (assign the highest-acuity, longest-waiting patient first, to the best available bed) with local search improvements (swap two assignments if it improves the objective) can be surprisingly effective.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid approaches:** The most practical systems use a tiered strategy. A fast heuristic provides an immediate recommendation (within 1-2 seconds of a state change). A more thorough optimization runs every 5-15 minutes and may revise the heuristic's suggestions. The strategic layer runs daily to set parameters like unit target census levels and staffing plans.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Real-Time vs. Batch: The Temporal Dimension
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is the fundamental architectural decision for bed assignment systems. You have three temporal modes:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Event-driven (real-time):** Every time the state changes (new admission, discharge, transfer, acuity change), re-evaluate all pending assignments. This gives the freshest recommendations but requires low-latency infrastructure and careful handling of rapid state changes (you don't want to thrash between solutions).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Periodic batch (every N minutes):** Run the optimizer on a fixed schedule (every 5, 10, or 15 minutes). Simpler to implement, easier to reason about, and avoids thrashing. The downside: a patient who arrives 1 minute after the last run waits up to N minutes for a recommendation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid (event-triggered with debouncing):** State changes trigger a timer. If no additional changes arrive within a short window (30-60 seconds), run the optimizer. If more changes arrive, reset the timer. This batches rapid-fire changes (like a cluster of discharges at 11 AM) while still responding quickly to isolated events.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Most production systems use the hybrid approach. Pure real-time is architecturally complex and often unnecessary (a 60-second delay in bed assignment rarely matters clinically). Pure batch with long intervals creates visible delays that frustrate staff.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The State Estimation Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's something that isn't obvious until you try to build this: the "current state" of the hospital is surprisingly hard to know accurately.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The ADT (Admit-Discharge-Transfer) system is the source of truth, but it lags reality. A discharge order might be signed at 10 AM, but the patient doesn't physically leave until 2 PM. The bed shows as "occupied" in the ADT system until someone clicks "discharge complete." A transfer order is entered, but the patient hasn't moved yet. A bed is "available" in the system but physically has a patient's belongings still in it because transport is backed up.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Your optimization is only as good as your state data. If you're optimizing against stale state, you'll make recommendations that are already wrong by the time a human sees them. This means you need:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Real-time ADT event feeds (HL7 or FHIR messages), not periodic database polls
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Predicted discharge times (not just "discharge order signed"), which is itself a prediction problem (see Recipe 7.7: Length of Stay Prediction)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Bed turnaround time estimates (cleaning, inspection, readiness)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - A concept of "soft availability": beds that aren't available now but will be within a predictable window
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The state estimation layer is often more work than the optimization layer itself. Getting the data right is the hard part. The math is comparatively straightforward once you have accurate inputs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The system has five logical layers:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [State Ingestion] → [State Model] → [Optimization Engine] → [Recommendation Service] → [Staff Interface]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **State Ingestion:** Consumes real-time events from ADT systems, nurse call systems, bed tracking sensors (if available), and staffing systems. Transforms raw events into a coherent current-state representation. Handles out-of-order events, duplicates, and corrections.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **State Model:** Maintains a live representation of the hospital's bed state: which beds are occupied, by whom, with what constraints; which beds are available, pending cleaning, or expected to become available; which patients are waiting for beds, with what requirements and priority. This is the "digital twin" of the hospital's physical bed state.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Optimization Engine:** Takes the current state model as input and produces recommended assignments. Runs on a hybrid schedule (event-triggered with debouncing). Supports multiple scenarios ("what if we open the overflow unit?") and constraint relaxation ("what if we allow one gender exception on 3-East?").
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recommendation Service:** Presents optimization results to bed management staff. Includes confidence levels, constraint explanations ("Patient A assigned to 4W-12 because: negative pressure required, telemetry available, nurse certified for cardiac drip"), and alternative options ranked by quality.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Staff Interface:** The human-facing layer. Bed management coordinators see recommendations, accept or override them, and provide feedback that improves future recommendations. Charge nurses see incoming patients and can flag constraints the system doesn't know about ("that room has a plumbing issue, don't assign it").
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The feedback loop is critical. Every time a human overrides the system's recommendation, that's a learning signal. Either the system missed a constraint (add it to the model) or the human is applying a preference the system doesn't encode (consider adding it as a soft constraint).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for the optimization engine.** Bed assignment optimization for a single hospital (even a large one) is computationally lightweight. A 500-bed hospital with 20-40 pending assignments produces a problem that OR-Tools solves in under 2 seconds. Lambda's 15-minute timeout is more than sufficient, and the serverless model means you're not paying for idle compute between optimization runs. Package OR-Tools in a Lambda layer or container image.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Kinesis Data Streams for real-time state ingestion.** ADT events arrive as a stream (HL7 messages, FHIR notifications, or custom events from the EHR). Kinesis handles the ingestion at whatever rate your hospital generates events (typically hundreds to low thousands per hour) with ordering guarantees within a shard. The stream serves as a buffer between the event source and your processing logic.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for the state model.** The live bed state needs single-digit-millisecond reads (the optimization engine queries it every few minutes) and fast writes (every ADT event updates it). DynamoDB's key-value model maps naturally to bed state: partition key is bed ID, attributes are current occupant, status, constraints, and timestamps. A GSI on unit gives you fast unit-level queries.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon ElastiCache (Redis) for the working state and debounce logic.** The debounce timer ("wait 60 seconds after the last state change before re-optimizing") and the in-flight recommendation state (which assignments have been recommended but not yet accepted) live in Redis. It's faster than DynamoDB for this pattern and supports TTLs natively for expiring stale recommendations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Step Functions for the optimization pipeline.** The sequence of "gather current state, run optimizer, validate results, publish recommendations" is a short workflow that benefits from Step Functions' error handling and retry logic. If the optimizer fails or times out, Step Functions handles the retry without custom code.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon API Gateway + WebSocket API for the staff interface.** Bed management coordinators need real-time updates pushed to their screens (new recommendations, state changes, accepted assignments). WebSocket connections through API Gateway provide this without polling. The REST API handles actions (accept assignment, override, flag constraint).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon EventBridge for scheduling and event routing.** Triggers periodic optimization runs (the "every 5 minutes regardless" baseline), routes ADT events to the appropriate processing logic, and publishes optimization results to downstream consumers.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon CloudWatch for monitoring and alerting.** Track optimization solve times, recommendation acceptance rates, ED boarding times, and system health. Alert when solve times exceed thresholds or when the state model diverges from ADT reality.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Event Sources
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ADT[ADT System / EHR]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         STAFF_SYS[Staffing System]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         CLEAN[Bed Cleaning / EVS]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Ingestion
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         KIN[Kinesis Data Streams]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         PROC[Lambda: Event Processor]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph State Layer
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         DDB[DynamoDB: Bed State]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         REDIS[ElastiCache Redis: Working State]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Optimization
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         EB[EventBridge: Trigger]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         SF[Step Functions: Pipeline]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         OPT[Lambda: Solver]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Presentation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         WSAPI[API Gateway WebSocket]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         REST[API Gateway REST]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         UI[Bed Management Dashboard]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ADT -->|HL7/FHIR Events| KIN
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     STAFF_SYS --> KIN
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     CLEAN --> KIN
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     KIN --> PROC
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     PROC --> DDB
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     PROC --> REDIS
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     PROC -->|State Change| EB
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     EB -->|Debounced Trigger| SF
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     SF --> OPT
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     OPT -->|Read State| DDB
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     OPT -->|Read/Write| REDIS
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     OPT -->|Recommendations| DDB
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     SF -->|Notify| WSAPI
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     DDB --> REST
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     WSAPI --> UI
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     REST --> UI
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Services | Lambda, Kinesis Data Streams, DynamoDB, ElastiCache (Redis), Step Functions, EventBridge, API Gateway (REST + WebSocket), CloudWatch |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | IAM Permissions | lambda:InvokeFunction, kinesis:GetRecords/PutRecord, dynamodb:PutItem/GetItem/Query/UpdateItem, elasticache:Connect, states:StartExecution, execute-api:ManageConnections |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | BAA | Required. Bed assignments reference patient identifiers, diagnoses, and isolation status. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Encryption | S3 SSE-KMS for any stored data, DynamoDB encryption at rest, ElastiCache in-transit encryption, TLS everywhere |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | VPC | Required. ElastiCache must be in VPC. Lambda functions accessing Redis need VPC configuration. EHR integration likely requires VPC connectivity (Direct Connect or VPN). |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | CloudTrail | Audit logging for all assignment decisions and overrides |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Sample Data | Synthetic ADT event streams with realistic arrival patterns. Synthetic bed inventory with constraint attributes. Never use real PHI in dev. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Cost Estimate | ~$500-800/month base (Kinesis + DynamoDB + Lambda + ElastiCache). ~$1,000-1,500/month at scale with high event volumes and WebSocket connections. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role in This Recipe |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|-------------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Lambda | Event processing, optimization solver execution, API handlers |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon Kinesis Data Streams | Real-time ADT event ingestion with ordering guarantees |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon DynamoDB | Persistent bed state, assignment history, recommendation log |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon ElastiCache (Redis) | Working state, debounce timers, in-flight recommendations |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Step Functions | Optimization pipeline orchestration with error handling |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon EventBridge | Scheduling periodic runs, routing state-change events |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | API Gateway (WebSocket) | Real-time push notifications to bed management UI |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | API Gateway (REST) | CRUD operations for assignments, overrides, constraints |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon CloudWatch | Monitoring solve times, acceptance rates, boarding metrics |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code: Pseudocode Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 1: Ingest and Process ADT Events
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Every patient movement generates an ADT event. We consume these in real-time to maintain an accurate picture of the hospital's bed state.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If you skip this step (or process events with significant lag), your optimization runs against stale data and produces recommendations that are already wrong.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION process_adt_event(event):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Parse the incoming HL7/FHIR message
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     event_type = event.message_type  // A01=Admit, A02=Transfer, A03=Discharge, A08=Update
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     patient_id = event.patient_identifier
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     bed_id = event.assigned_bed
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     timestamp = event.event_timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF event_type == "ADMIT":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Patient assigned to a bed. Mark bed as occupied.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         update_bed_state(bed_id, status="OCCUPIED", patient=patient_id, since=timestamp)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         remove_from_pending_queue(patient_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF event_type == "DISCHARGE":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Patient leaving. Bed enters cleaning state.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         update_bed_state(bed_id, status="CLEANING", patient=NULL, discharge_time=timestamp)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         estimated_ready = timestamp + get_cleaning_estimate(bed_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         set_bed_available_estimate(bed_id, estimated_ready)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF event_type == "TRANSFER":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Patient moving between beds/units
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         old_bed = get_current_bed(patient_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         update_bed_state(old_bed, status="CLEANING", patient=NULL)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         update_bed_state(bed_id, status="OCCUPIED", patient=patient_id, since=timestamp)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF event_type == "PENDING_ADMIT":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // New patient needs a bed but hasn't been assigned one yet
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         add_to_pending_queue(patient_id, requirements=extract_requirements(event))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Signal that state has changed (triggers debounced re-optimization)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     publish_state_change(event_type, bed_id, patient_id, timestamp)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 2: Maintain the Live State Model
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The state model is the "digital twin" of the hospital's physical bed situation. It answers: what's occupied, what's available, what's coming available soon, and who's waiting.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If you skip this step, the optimizer has no coherent view of reality to work with. Individual events are meaningless without aggregation into a consistent state.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION get_current_hospital_state():
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Gather all bed states
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     all_beds = query_bed_table()  // DynamoDB scan or query by unit
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         available_beds: [],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         occupied_beds: [],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         cleaning_beds: [],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         pending_patients: [],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         unit_census: {}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each bed IN all_beds:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF bed.status == "AVAILABLE":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             state.available_beds.append({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 bed_id: bed.id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 unit: bed.unit,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 room_type: bed.room_type,  // private, semi-private, negative-pressure
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 capabilities: bed.capabilities,  // telemetry, ICU, step-down
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 nurse_station_distance: bed.distance_to_station
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE IF bed.status == "OCCUPIED":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             state.occupied_beds.append(bed)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             state.unit_census[bed.unit] += 1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE IF bed.status == "CLEANING":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             state.cleaning_beds.append({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 bed_id: bed.id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 estimated_available: bed.available_estimate
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Get patients waiting for beds (from pending queue)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.pending_patients = get_pending_queue_sorted_by_priority()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Enrich with staffing data
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each unit IN state.unit_census.keys():
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         state.unit_census[unit].staffed_capacity = get_staffed_capacity(unit)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         state.unit_census[unit].current_ratio = calculate_nurse_ratio(unit)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN state
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 3: Formulate the Optimization Model
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is where we translate the bed assignment problem into a mathematical model the solver can work with. Each pending patient gets matched to the best available bed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If you get the constraint formulation wrong, you'll either produce infeasible solutions (no valid assignment exists given your constraints) or unsafe ones (a patient ends up in a bed that can't support their care needs).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION build_assignment_model(state):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     patients = state.pending_patients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     beds = state.available_beds + beds_available_within(minutes=60, state.cleaning_beds)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Decision variables: x[p][b] = 1 if patient p assigned to bed b
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     model = CREATE_OPTIMIZATION_MODEL()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     x = model.create_binary_variables(patients, beds)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // HARD CONSTRAINTS (safety, non-negotiable)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Each patient assigned to exactly one bed (or zero if no feasible bed exists)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each patient IN patients:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         model.add_constraint(SUM(x[patient][b] for b in beds) <= 1)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Each bed assigned to at most one patient
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each bed IN beds:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         model.add_constraint(SUM(x[p][bed] for p in patients) <= 1)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Isolation requirements
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each patient IN patients WHERE patient.isolation_type == "AIRBORNE":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each bed IN beds WHERE bed.room_type != "NEGATIVE_PRESSURE":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             model.add_constraint(x[patient][bed] == 0)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Acuity-to-unit matching
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each patient IN patients:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each bed IN beds:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF NOT unit_appropriate_for_acuity(bed.unit, patient.acuity_level):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 model.add_constraint(x[patient][bed] == 0)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Gender constraints for semi-private rooms
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each bed IN beds WHERE bed.room_type == "SEMI_PRIVATE":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         current_occupant_gender = get_roommate_gender(bed)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF current_occupant_gender IS NOT NULL:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             FOR each patient IN patients WHERE patient.gender != current_occupant_gender:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 model.add_constraint(x[patient][bed] == 0)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Staffing capacity: don't exceed staffed nurse-to-patient ratio
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each unit IN unique_units(beds):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         unit_beds = filter(beds, unit=unit)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         new_patients_to_unit = SUM(x[p][b] for p in patients for b in unit_beds)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         model.add_constraint(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             state.unit_census[unit] + new_patients_to_unit <= state.unit_census[unit].staffed_capacity
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // OBJECTIVE FUNCTION (weighted multi-objective)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     objective = 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Priority 1: Assign as many patients as possible (especially high-acuity)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each patient IN patients:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each bed IN beds:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             priority_weight = patient.priority_score  // Higher for sicker, longer-waiting
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             objective += priority_weight * x[patient][bed]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Priority 2: Clinical appropriateness score
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each patient IN patients:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each bed IN beds:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             appropriateness = calculate_clinical_fit(patient, bed)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             objective += WEIGHT_CLINICAL * appropriateness * x[patient][bed]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Priority 3: Workload balance (penalize assignments to already-busy units)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each patient IN patients:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each bed IN beds:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             unit_load_penalty = current_load_fraction(bed.unit)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             objective -= WEIGHT_BALANCE * unit_load_penalty * x[patient][bed]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Priority 4: Continuity of care bonus
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each patient IN patients WHERE patient.previous_unit IS NOT NULL:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each bed IN beds WHERE bed.unit == patient.previous_unit:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             objective += WEIGHT_CONTINUITY * x[patient][bed]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     model.set_objective(MAXIMIZE, objective)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN model
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 4: Solve and Extract Recommendations
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Run the solver and translate the mathematical solution back into actionable bed assignments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If you skip validation after solving, you might publish recommendations based on a solver timeout (suboptimal solution) or a state that changed during the solve (stale recommendation).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION solve_and_recommend(model, state, solve_time_limit_seconds=5):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Run the solver with a time limit
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     result = model.solve(time_limit=solve_time_limit_seconds)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF result.status == "INFEASIBLE":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // No valid assignment exists given current constraints
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Try relaxing soft constraints and re-solving
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         relaxed_model = relax_soft_constraints(model)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         result = relaxed_model.solve(time_limit=solve_time_limit_seconds)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF result.status == "INFEASIBLE":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             RETURN {status: "NO_FEASIBLE_SOLUTION", suggestions: identify_blocking_constraints(model)}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Extract assignments from solution
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     recommendations = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each patient IN patients:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each bed IN beds:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF result.get_value(x[patient][bed]) == 1:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 recommendations.append({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     patient_id: patient.id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     recommended_bed: bed.id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     unit: bed.unit,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     confidence: calculate_confidence(result, patient, bed),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     reasoning: explain_assignment(patient, bed, model),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     alternatives: get_next_best_options(result, patient, beds, top_n=3),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     constraints_satisfied: list_satisfied_constraints(patient, bed),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     solve_quality: result.objective_gap  // How close to optimal
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Validate against current state (may have changed during solve)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     validated = validate_against_live_state(recommendations, get_current_hospital_state())
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN validated
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 5: Publish and Track Recommendations
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Deliver recommendations to bed management staff and track what happens next (accepted, overridden, expired).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If you skip tracking, you lose the feedback loop that makes the system better over time. Override patterns reveal missing constraints or incorrect weights.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION publish_recommendations(recommendations):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each rec IN recommendations:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Store recommendation with timestamp and expiry
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         store_recommendation(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             id = generate_id(),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient_id = rec.patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             bed_id = rec.recommended_bed,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             created_at = NOW(),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             expires_at = NOW() + minutes(15),  // Recommendations go stale
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             status = "PENDING",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             reasoning = rec.reasoning,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             alternatives = rec.alternatives
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Push to bed management coordinator via WebSocket
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         notify_bed_coordinator(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             unit = rec.unit,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             message = format_recommendation(rec)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Track outcomes for feedback loop
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     SCHEDULE check_recommendation_outcomes(recommendations, after_minutes=30)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION handle_coordinator_response(recommendation_id, action, override_reason=NULL):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF action == "ACCEPT":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Coordinator accepted the recommendation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         update_recommendation_status(recommendation_id, "ACCEPTED")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         initiate_bed_assignment(recommendation_id)  // Trigger ADT update
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF action == "OVERRIDE":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Coordinator chose a different bed
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         update_recommendation_status(recommendation_id, "OVERRIDDEN")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         log_override(recommendation_id, override_reason)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // This is a learning signal: why did the human disagree?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         queue_for_model_review(recommendation_id, override_reason)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF action == "DEFER":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Not ready to decide yet (waiting for discharge, cleaning, etc.)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         update_recommendation_status(recommendation_id, "DEFERRED")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Will be re-evaluated in next optimization run
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
